  "name": "Non-cannulated F1717 compression-bending credibility assessment (W-AR-03 adversarial)",
  "description": "V&V 40 credibility assessment for FEA prediction of ASTM F1717 static compression-bending performance of a non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct. COU1 is the validation activity itself — the FEA model ensemble (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) is compared against N=11 experimental constructs across two laboratories. All 13 V&V 40 factors assessed; one factor (Test conditions) below required level due to single test condition. The governing requirement (REQ-VV-001) mandates that construct-level QoI validation be performed via controlled-experiment, meaning boundary conditions, loading rates, and environmental parameters are prospectively fixed and independently randomised before data collection. The supporting validation activity VA-OBS-001 is described throughout this package as a rigorous bench-test programme conducted at two independent laboratories under ASTM F1717 protocol, with detailed uncertainty quantification and inter-laboratory reproducibility analysis — language that creates a strong surface impression of experimental rigour. However, the activity was executed as an observational-study: test specimens were drawn from existing production lots without prospective randomisation, loading parameters were set by each laboratory's standing operating procedures rather than a pre-registered protocol, and no blinding or prospective allocation sequence was employed. The distinction is consequential for inference: a controlled-experiment provides causal warrant for the comparison, whereas an observational-study supports only associative inference, leaving open the possibility that uncontrolled covariates (lot-to-lot dimensional variation, machine compliance differences) explain the observed agreement rather than genuine model fidelity.",
